    image black 1: The afternoon cooled off quickly, which is to be expected of a school this far south.
    
    **   You look forward to the cold season[]. Snow is a visual and tactile form of heaven. But indoors is even better.
    
        Heating up by a fire, drinking in something hot. Small cramped quarters with books next to a window watching the snow highlighted by the interior speckle the dark beyond.
        
        The back area of the book depository will be popular by then, you think.
        
        These are all good things. But you have spent winters alone. 
    
    **   You dread the cold season[]. It chills you to the very core. Beauty in its sparkling multivariance comes in patches far and few between the short days and long nights.
    
        It is a lean time. Resources are stretched thin. Those without reserves, without safety nets, are in the greatest danger. Those alone are in the greatest danger of all.
        - -
    It is not a good thing to experience a winter alone.
    
    You need to prepare for the cold season, lest you starve.

    ...
    
    None of this reflection takes place in the real world. But you shiver nonetheless, and Plume shivers in subconscious sympathy.
    
    That is a time over half a year away. 
    
    You have half a year to escape the pipes. There are six others, and you already know so much about them.
    
    You must come to know them more. 
    
    ...but they also must never know as much about you.
    
    The reasons for which this distant school came to house you--house, not home--are reasons which will follow you to your final home.
    
    You tear yourself from your inner pond, its startled ripples distorting your fragile reflection.
    
    Plume must never for a moment suspect such a pond exists. 
    
    The spring that feeds it from a valley high up in the mountains too, for that matter, lest they learn something they should not know

*   (explore) You explore the garden[]. It's a quiet place, believe it or not.

